Introduction¶

Soccer database originally posted on Kaggle (https://www.kaggle.com/hugomathien/soccer) is selected for analysis.

From this dataset we are interested in knowing:

  • What teams improved the most over the time period?
  • Which players had the most penalties?
  • What team attributes lead to the most victories?
  • Is there any performance difference between the left-footed and right-footed players?
  • What are the attributes of top 10 players?

Setup¶

Since the original database is in SQL format, these lines are executed to bring the data into Pandas dataframe All the subsequent work is done in Pandas Each table in the original databse is moved into a new dataframe in Pandas

The Match dataset has 115 columns which makes it cumbersome to work with so I decided to bring the first 11 columns only The remaining columns in Match dataset are related to the players positions in the games and betting acronyms which I am not going to use here

Data Wrangling¶

The Kaggle page provides a very convenient overview of what the data looks like, therefore some of the preliminary steps can be skipped here as the information is available there. Here is the list of information that was gained by looking at the Kaggle page using "column view"

  • Country is 11x2, has no missing values, foreign key: id
  • League is 11x3, has no missing values, foreign key: country_id
  • Match is 26k x 115 however we trimmed it to 26k x 11, has no missing values on the selected 11 columns, foreign keys: country_id,league_id,home_team_api_id,away_team_api_id
  • Player is 11.1k x 7, has no missing values, foreign key: player_api_id
  • Player_Attributes is 184k x 42, has various missing values as tested below ,foreign key: player_api_id
  • Team is 299 x 5, has limited missing values on column team_fifa_api_id which we will not use, foreign key: team_api_id
  • Team_Attributes is 1458 x 25, has 969 missing values on column buildUpPlayDribbling which we will not use, foreign key: team_api_id

Data preparation for question 1: What teams improved the most over the time period?¶

For checking team improvement over time period, we could perhaps look at the information given inTeam_Attributes and get a sense of team attributes over time however although this would be an indicative of the team performance, ultimately winning the matches is the most important factor. Because of this, I decided to look at the Match and check how many games each team won during the time period over several seasons to establish an improvement index for each team. The dataframe has the number of home_team_goal and away_team_goal so we can create 2 columns that represent the point each team gained for that match. For this the standard European league point system is used where the winner takes 3 points, loser takes 0 point and a tie results in 1 point for each team. This index will be used to compare the performance of each team yearly. Since we are dealing with dataframes Match and Team, we don't do any data cleaning and only joining between these two is required. In order to be able to make seasonal comparision, the column season also needs conversion from string to numeric.

In [5]:
# Data preparation for question 1
# Adding the point columns to 'Match'

# Function to calculate the point based on European Football system
def point(col1, col2):
    goal_diff = col1 - col2
    if goal_diff > 0:
        return 3
    elif goal_diff == 0:
        return 1
    else:
        return 0
        
# Create two new columns for the teams points
df_match['home_team_point'] = df_match.apply(lambda x: point(x.home_team_goal,x.away_team_goal),axis=1)
df_match['away_team_point'] = df_match.apply(lambda x: point(x.away_team_goal,x.home_team_goal),axis=1)

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Research Question 1: What teams improved the most over the time period?¶

Now that we have cleaned up 'Match' dataset and have the score of each team available. we can go through a few steps to establish an "improvement index". The steps would be:

  • Find the total point each team accumulated on each season
  • Do a linear regression fit over the total point of each team where x-axis would be season and y-axis would be total points
  • Check the slope of the linear regression line for each team and find the steepest slope which implies the best team progress over several seasons

        m,b = np.polyfit(x, y, 1)

    m_all[h] = m

Limitations¶

This study encompasses few limitations which we discuss below based on the question we are trying to answer:

Q1: What teams improved the most over the time period? The method we utilized here is based on the linear regression and determining the steepest slope. While this mathematically is a sound approach, linear regression really excels when there is a reasonable amount of data available. In this study, we selected the season as one of the variables which depending on the team's appearance in the game, could vary from 1 to 8 seasons. One season appearance would be meaningless to begin with and the teams with 2 appearance, even though it is possible to fit a line through, yields low confidence in the analysis. Incidentally, the team we found to have the steepest slope, meaning greatest seasonal improvement, happened to be a team that only appeared in 2 seasons. Therefore, this puts some limitations on the strength of the chosen method that needs to be taken into account

Q2: Which players had the most penalties? The main limitation is the fact that the value we used is assumed to be the right value to look at. My preliminary investigation on whether this value means this is the number of the penalties a player scored did not find anything. Therefore, the results shown for this analysis rely on this assumption being true.

Q3: What team attributes lead to the most victories? The plots as illustrated above did not show any strong relationship between the teams’ victory and the team attributes. This was done purely based on the visualizations and without any statistical analysis such as Pearson correlation or likewise. To better quantify the relation, it would be useful to carry out some statistical analysis and establish the correlations quantitatively

Q4: Is there any performance difference between the left-footed and right-footed players? This analysis, same as above, was an illustrative analysis and there is not significant analytical analyses done on this. There are potential to improve the comparison made in this section by carrying out further quantitative investigation

Q5: What are the attributes of top 10 players? We limited the study to top 10 players and did the analysis based on the available available attributes. The overall rating where the ranking of the top 10 players was based upon is just one number selected from the table and there might be more inclusive way to rank the players from top to bottom rather than looking at one number

Conclusions¶

  • SQL import to Pandas is very smooth and works quite well. Here I decided to do all the wranging after importing the data into Pandas, however it is optionally possible to run some SQL commands for pre-work
  • What teams improved the most over the time period? It looks like Leicester City was the winner. However it should be noted that the data of this team is available only for 2 seasons. One can argue that for better credibility of the results, this analysis should only include the teams with more seasonal appearance
  • Which players had the most penalties? Assuming the 'penalties' values found in 'player attributes' dataframe is the correct data to look at, it is found that Rickie Lambert is the winner
  • What team attributes lead to the most victories? The data does not present any strong relation between the team attributes and the winning. Some of the indexes show some weak positive relation but overall the analysis does not show a strong relation between them
  • Is there any performance difference between the left-footed and right-footed players? It looks like the left-footed players appear to stand out in majority of the player attributes. There are only 4 last indexes where they are below the right-footed players, otherwise they seem the excel consistently
  • What are the attributes of top 10 players? They excel in all player attributes by a factor of 3 to 4 from the mean values of all players. Plotting them in the bar format shows also a general decay of these values from player No. 1 to 10 gradually.
